  "doc_id": "27400",
  "text": "The GABA-A receptor agonist muscimol and the GABA-B receptor agonist (RS)-baclofen (Tocris Bioscience, UK) were dissolved in saline. In all regions 1.0 nmol/0.3 ml baclofen and 0.1 nmol/0.3 ml muscimol (B&M) was administered, with the exception of the NAcc shell into which 0.1 nmol/0.3 ml baclofen and 0.01 nmol/0.3 ml muscimol was infused. Lower doses of B&M were infused into the NAcc shell because the 1.0 nmol baclofen/0.1 nmol muscimol dose caused intense, non-specific hyperphagia (see eg, [CITATION_1] , which resulted in a complete blockade of social play. The AMPA/kainate receptor antagonist, 6,7-dinitroquinoxaline-2,3(1H,4H)-dione (DNQX) (Sigma, USA), was dissolved in 50% DMSO in saline, and a dose of 3.0 nmol/0.3 ml was administered. Infusion procedures were as previously described [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In short, bilateral infusions of drugs or equivalent volume of saline were administered using 30-gauge injection needles (Bilaney, Germany) connected to 10 ml Hamilton micro-syringes by polyethylene tubing. Over 60 s, 0.3 ml of the solution was infused using a syringe pump (Harvard Apparatus, USA). The injection needles remained within the guide cannulae for 60 s following drug infusion to facilitate diffusion and to prevent backflow of drug along the cannula track. After the infusion, the stylets were replaced.",
